Interview Questions
1) What are iteration statements in Java?
-->Iteration statements (loops) are used to execute a block of code repeatedly until a condition becomes false.
    👉 Types:
          for
          while
          do-while
          for-each (enhanced for loop)


2) Difference between for, while, and do-while loops..
-->
| Feature         | for loop         | while loop         | do-while loop |
| --------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ | ------------- |
| Condition check | Before loop      | Before loop        | After loop    |
| Execution       | 0 or more times  | 0 or more times    | At least once |
| Use case        | Known iterations | Unknown iterations | Must run once |



3) Which loop is entry-controlled and which is exit-controlled?
-->Entry-controlled loops: for, while
      👉 Condition checked before execution
      Exit-controlled loop: do-while
      👉 Condition checked after execution



4) Explain the syntax of a for, while ,do-while ,for -each loop in Java.
-->✅ for loop
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
            System.out.println(i);
        }

        ✅ while loop
        int i = 0;
        while (i < 5) {
            System.out.println(i);
            i++;
        }

        ✅ do-while loop
        int i = 0;
        do {
            System.out.println(i);
            i++;
        } while (i < 5);

        ✅ for-each loop
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
        for (int num : arr) {
            System.out.println(num);
        }



5) Can we have an infinite loop? How to create it by using for, while Give an example.
-->✅ Yes:
      Using for
      for (;;) {
          System.out.println("Infinite");
      }

      Using while
      while (true) {
          System.out.println("Infinite");
      }


6) What is the difference between for and for-each loop?
-->
| Feature                     | for loop     | for-each loop |
| --------------------------- | ------------ | ------------- |
| Index access                | Yes          | No            |
| Direction control           | Yes          | No            |
| Works on arrays/collections | Yes          | Yes           |
| Simplicity                  | More complex | Simple        |



7) When is a for loop preferred over a while loop?
-->Use for when:
    Number of iterations is known
    You need an index variable



8) When is a do-while loop used?
-->Use do-while when:
    Code must run at least once
    👉 Example: menu-driven programs


9) How do break and continue work in loops?
-->break 👉 exits the loop completely
    continue 👉 skips current iteration and goes to next
    for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
        if (i == 3) continue;
        if (i == 5) break;
        System.out.println(i);
    }


10) What is the difference between break and return inside a loop?
-->
| Feature      | break                | return                 |
| ------------ | -------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Scope        | Exits loop only      | Exits entire method    |
| Program flow | Continues after loop | Stops method execution |


11) What happens if we put a continue statement in the last line of a loop?
-->👉 No effect difference  Because control already goes to the next iteration.



12) Can loops be replaced with recursion? When is that useful?
-->✅ Yes
    👉 Recursion = function calling itself
    
    Use when:
    Problem is recursive in nature (tree, factorial, etc.)
    ⚠️ But loops are usually more efficient (less memory).


13) When should we use a for loop, a while loop, or a for-each loop in Java?
-->for loop 👉 when iterations are known
    while loop 👉 when condition-based repetition
    for-each 👉 when iterating arrays/collections (read-only)

